IBM history: From cheese cutter to all over the world
The IBM (International Business Machines) company, founded a hundred years ago in New York, initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Corporation.
The name IBM took over it only in 1924 - originally it was a trademark name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation stone for the later IBM society laid the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They had technologies such as the famous Stech card watches to register the start and end of work.
The architect of this new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who also had the chair of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who appointed the head of the competition company Thomas J. Watson to help him manage the company.
This leader even put the founders of IBM in the shade - based on Watson's ideas to this day the invincible culture and identity of the company.
Watson headed the company until 1952.
IBM, as already the name reveals, began with the manufacture and distribution of all possible machines for trade - from sausage and cheese cutters, to checkouts.
In the first four decades in which Watson led the company, he doubled her sales to $9 million and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he was sitting in the chair for all forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under its direction IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, technicians and computers from IBM helped lead NASA flights to space - to Mercury and Saturn and in 1969 also the famous flight of man to the moon.
Meanwhile, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture in 1964 - the series IBM System/360.
A classic PC that determined the computer standard of that time came to the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consultant's share of PricewaterhouseCooper and thus became fully involved in the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM pays out over the last three years is the concept of "Smarter Planet".
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in areas that have not even been planned so far, e.g. to improve the situation in traffic and in urban administration.
In the trade sector, IBM recently introduced the "Smarter Commerce" platform to help dealers lead the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
IBM founded a branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932 - as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe at all.
Today IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
Central for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague, and here is also a top research team of world-levels that deals with voting recognition technology.
