Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, the ČSSR had only five approved state travel agencies: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies sold mainly travels to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries at the time, and in the West only elected ones were allowed.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic (in the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the peninsula of Crimea on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972 when they were allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore the journeys to Yugoslavia were severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that it was not even allowed citizens of the East Block (also Czechoslovakia) to travel freely within the context of socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travels were not possible.
Back then, travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but then they had to buy huge snakes or stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, the thing hasn't been done for a long time.
The so-called currency allocation - the condition for leaving the West - was granted only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to raise the necessary funding (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The vast majority of the Czechs therefore spent their vacation in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dates - a habit that continues to this day.
The total revolution of 1989 followed a travel revolution of the Czechs.
While a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries around the world.
A huge paradox, which is no longer known today, is the fact that one could not travel to the most popular holiday country in the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989 at all because it was part of Yugoslavia at that time.
Right from the beginning of the 1990s, foreign exchange obligation was lifted in the neighbouring Western European countries, which brought about a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovakians could not get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
The Czech holidaymakers slept in the park while traveling to Paris in the tent, because who had already had the money for accommodation in the hotel or in a pension at that time.
A typical feature of travel abroad from the Czech Republic was a trunk packed with canned, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our level of living and therefore average salaries increased, which resulted in another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, the travel agencies began to prepare regular trips through charter flights after 1997, making travels incredibly acceptable in comparison to the past thanks to the opportunity to negotiate quantity discounts.
At the end of the 1990s, with the exception of the United States, the Czechs had foreign payments with all the highly developed countries in the world, which made traveling even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-salt" travel came in 2000, when thanks to the high demand the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was completed - to Thailand.
Since then, every year direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers fly in far sunny countries; this year twelve exotic destinations are taken directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100th Czechs travel annually in exotic countries!
Another important moment in the epoch that marked our post-revolutionary development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the US raised visa requirements for Czech tourists, which definitely led our country to join the highly developed countries of the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) for the first time and for the first time in their history spent more than 15 cents of CZK per head for a single holiday, including the cost of the holiday resort.
