The decline in economic activity until November has led to a steady increase in unemployment in the Mexican state. In the first quarter of the year, the Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment, as from January to March 55 053 inhabitants did not have Sinaloas, which corresponds to 4.53 percent of the labour force. In the second quarter the unemployment rate increased to 5.28 percent and from July to September to 6.19 percent, resulting in 74 000 unemployed people in Sinaloa.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa in the year goes down to several factors. Economic scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), commented that the policies of public institutions indirectly explain growing unemployment.
