Asphalt from the UNAM prevents impact holes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University of UNAM develops modified asphaltes with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs from the road cover were respected, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 blowholes if the rainy season broke out in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (City Area of the Valley of Mexico), Rafael Herrera Najera, researchers at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, warned and assured that if the laying out and maintenance of the asphalt coating were properly scrambled, the number of stroke holes would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Schlaglöcher from a technical point of view", which he held on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he was responsible developed modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, which, however, has greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Najera said that this kind of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of the street cover and thus avoid the occurrence of impact holes.
He stated that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound from which a part has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalt - and the other part a low - the so-called malthene. Together they give the road cover its characteristic toughness behavior.
Teeth elasticity of asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very tough and almost solid at 50°C, while it becomes fragile at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of asphalt on the streets is not uniform, but changes on one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer explained.
The researcher of the FQ noted that the streets of Mexico City had a flexible road cover, composed of six layers of materials, of which the last three were asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a wear layer of asphalt that is bathed in small asphalt and then fixed stones.
Every single stone of this wear layer has been bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move forward and power is created, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
